# Functions
myflextable = function(data, ...) {
  set_flextable_defaults(na_str = "NA", theme_fun = theme_booktabs, font.size = 12, padding.bottom = 1, padding.top = 1)
  x = flextable(data, ...)
  x = colformat_int(x, big.mark = "")
  x = colformat_double(x, big.mark = "", digits = 2, na_str = "NA")
  return(x)
}

Load data

# hourly temps
washingtonDC_tbl = readRDS(here::here("data","small_washingtonDC_hrly_temp.rds"))

vancouver_tbl = readRDS(here::here("data","small_vancouver_hrly_temp.rds"))

Add Julian days (day of year)

washingtonDC_tbl = washingtonDC_tbl %>% 
  mutate(JDay = yday(datetime)) %>% 
  rename(Year=yr, Hour=hr, Temp=temp)
kyoto_tbl = kyoto_tbl %>%
  mutate(JDay = yday(datetime)) %>% 
  rename(Year=yr, Hour=hr, Temp=temp)
basel_tbl = basel_tbl %>% 
  mutate(JDay = yday(datetime)) %>% 
  rename(Year=yr, Hour=hr, Temp=temp)
vancouver_tbl = vancouver_tbl %>% 
  mutate(JDay = yday(datetime)) %>% 
  rename(Year=yr, Hour=hr, Temp=temp)

Chilling calcs require DF

washington_DF = washingtonDC_tbl %>% select(Year, Month=mon, Day=day, Hour, Temp, JDay) %>% as.data.frame()
kyoto_DF = kyoto_tbl %>% select(Year, Month=mon, Day=day, Hour, Temp, JDay) %>% as.data.frame()
basel_DF = basel_tbl %>% select(Year, Month=mon, Day=day, Hour, Temp, JDay) %>% as.data.frame()
vancouver_DF = vancouver_tbl %>% select(Year, Month=mon, Day=day, Hour, Temp, JDay) %>% as.data.frame()

The chilling function calculates Chill Portions using Dynamic model default parameters. As the original publication said that these parameters should be cultivar and location specific, this is just for comparative interest and to see where the most missing data is.

washington_chilling = chilling(washington_DF, 305, 60)
kyoto_chilling = chilling(kyoto_DF, 305, 60)
basel_chilling = chilling(basel_DF, 305, 60)
vancouver_chilling = chilling(vancouver_DF, 305, 60)
bind_rows(tail(washington_chilling,5) %>% add_column(Location = "Washington DC", .before = 1),
          tail(basel_chilling, 5) %>% add_column(Location = "Basel, CH", .before = 1),
          tail(kyoto_chilling, 5) %>% add_column(Location = "Kyoto, JP", .before = 1),
          tail(vancouver_chilling,5) %>% add_column(Location = "Vancouver, CA", .before = 1))

PhenoFlex

iSeason_DC = genSeason(washington_DF, years = c(2009))
yc = 40
zc = 190
res_DC = PhenoFlex(temp=washington_DF$Temp[iSeason_DC[[1]]],
                 times=c(1: length(washington_DF$Temp[iSeason_DC[[1]]])),
                 zc=zc, stopatzc=TRUE, yc=yc, basic_output=FALSE)

Graphs of chill and heat accumulation

DBreakDay <- res_DC$bloomindex
seasontemps<-washington_DF[iSeason_DC[[1]],]
seasontemps[,"x"]<-res_DC$x
seasontemps[,"y"]<-res_DC$y
seasontemps[,"z"]<-res_DC$z
seasontemps<-add_date(seasontemps)

ggplot(data=seasontemps[1:DBreakDay,],aes(x=Date,y=y)) +
  geom_line(col="blue",lwd=1.5) +
  theme_bw(base_size=20) +
  geom_hline(yintercept=yc,lty=2) +
  labs(title="Chill (y) accumulation")

ggplot(data=seasontemps[1:DBreakDay,],aes(x=Date,y=z)) +
  geom_line(col="red",lwd=1.5) +
  theme_bw(base_size=20) +
  geom_hline(yintercept=zc,lty=2) +
  labs(title="Heat (z) accumulation")

# years with sufficient data
season_years_washington = c(1938:1945, 1947:1965, 1974:2021)
SeasonList = genSeasonList(washington_DF, mrange = c(11,5), years = season_years_washington)# The ‘years‘ argument specifies the year, in which the dormancy season of interest ends.
# PhenoFlex default param ranges
par <-   c(40, 190, 0.5, 25, 3372.8,  9900.3, 6319.5, 5.939917e13,  4, 36,  4,  1.60)
upper <- c(41, 200, 1.0, 30, 4000.0, 10000.0, 7000.0,       6.e13, 10, 40, 10, 50.00)
lower <- c(38, 180, 0.1, 0 , 3000.0,  9000.0, 6000.0,       5.e13,  0,  0,  0,  0.05)

if (rerun_simann) {
  SEED = 123
  s=Sys.time()
  Fit_res_washington = phenologyFitter(par.guess=par, 
                             modelfn = PhenoFlex_GDHwrapper,
                             bloomJDays=bloom_dc$bloom_doy[which(bloom_dc$year %in% season_years_washington)],
                             SeasonList=SeasonList, lower=lower, upper=upper,
                             control=list(smooth=FALSE, verbose=TRUE, maxit=1000,
                                          nb.stop.improvement=250),
                             seed = SEED)
  Sys.time() - s
  saveRDS(Fit_res_washington, here::here("data", "sim_ann_res_washington.rds"))
} else {
  Fit_res_washington = readRDS(here::here("data","sim_ann_res_washington.rds"))
}

function to run PhenoFlex for every season to get the Chill Portions and heat accumulation

calc_model_outputs = function (input_DF, blooming_year, sim_ann_res) {
  iSeason = genSeason(input_DF, mrange = c(11,5), years = blooming_year)
  predicted_res = PhenoFlex(temp = input_DF$Temp[iSeason[[1]]],
                 times = c(1: length(input_DF$Temp[iSeason[[1]]])),
                 zc = sim_ann_res$par[2],
                 stopatzc = TRUE,
                 yc = sim_ann_res$par[1],
                 basic_output = FALSE,
                 s1 = sim_ann_res$par[3],
                 Tu = sim_ann_res$par[4],
                 E0 = sim_ann_res$par[5],
                 E1 = sim_ann_res$par[6],
                 A0 = sim_ann_res$par[7],
                 A1 = sim_ann_res$par[8],
                 Tf = sim_ann_res$par[9],
                 Tc = sim_ann_res$par[10],
                 Tb = sim_ann_res$par[11],
                 slope = sim_ann_res$par[12],
                 )
  
  plotdat = tibble(
    blooming_year = blooming_year,
    datetime = make_datetime(year = input_DF$Year[iSeason[[1]]], 
                             month = input_DF$Month[iSeason[[1]]],
                             day = input_DF$Day[iSeason[[1]]],
                             hour = input_DF$Hour[iSeason[[1]]]),
    jday = input_DF$JDay[iSeason[[1]]],
    temp = input_DF$Temp[iSeason[[1]]],
    times = c(1:length(input_DF$Temp[iSeason[[1]]])),
    res_x =  predicted_res[[1]],
    res_y =  predicted_res[[2]],
    res_z =  predicted_res[[3]],
    res_xs = predicted_res[[4]]
  )
  plotdat.long = pivot_longer(plotdat, c(temp, starts_with("res_")))
  return(plotdat.long)
}

What could happen in Basel in 2022?

Using data up until the latest available for the season 2021-2022, I replace previous years’ Nov-now data with this year’s, and then see what would have happened had the years continued in the way in which they did. I also interpolate some missing hourly data at this point.

replacement_basel_DF = basel_DF %>% filter(Month %in% c(1:5,11,12), Year >= 2001)
replacement_basel_2022 = replacement_basel_DF %>% filter(Year==2022 | (Year==2021 & Month %in% 11:12)) %>% add_date
replacement_basel_2022 %>% count(Month, Day) %>% count(n) # not too much missing
b2022int = interpolate_gaps_hourly(hourtemps=replacement_basel_2022, latitude=47.4814)$weather %>% add_date

ggplot() + geom_point(b2022int %>% filter(!Date %in% replacement_basel_2022$Date), mapping=aes(x=Date, y=Temp), colour="black") + geom_line(replacement_basel_2022, mapping=aes(x=Date, y=Temp), colour="red")

replace_basel_all = bind_rows(b2022int %>% select(Year, Month, Day, Hour, Temp))
for (i in seq_along(season_years_basel)){
  replace_basel_all = bind_rows(replace_basel_all,
  b2022int %>% 
    select(Year, Month, Day, Hour, Temp) %>% 
    mutate(Year = (Year - 21 + i))
  )
}
head(basel_DF %>% filter(Year==2001, Month==11))
replacement_basel_DF_final = replacement_basel_DF %>% 
  rows_upsert(replace_basel_all, by = c("Year", "Month", "Day", "Hour")) %>% 
  group_by(Year, Month, Day) %>% 
  mutate(Date = ISOdate(Year, Month, Day, Hour),
         JDay = yday(Date)) %>% # without this there are NAs in the JDay and the traces separate a bit early
  ungroup() %>% 
  arrange(Date)
head(replacement_basel_DF_final, 10)

Interpolate Vancouver data

replacement_vancouver_DF = vancouver_DF %>% filter(Month %in% c(1:5,11,12), Year >= 1977)
replacement_vancouver_2022 = replacement_vancouver_DF %>% filter(Year==2022 | (Year==2021 & Month %in% 11:12)) %>% add_date
replacement_vancouver_2022 %>% count(Month, Day) %>% count(n) # not too much missing
vancouver2022int = interpolate_gaps_hourly(hourtemps=replacement_vancouver_2022, latitude=49.2237)$weather %>% add_date

ggplot() + geom_line(replacement_vancouver_2022, mapping=aes(x=Date, y=Temp), colour="red") + geom_point(vancouver2022int %>% filter(!Date %in% replacement_vancouver_2022$Date), mapping=aes(x=Date, y=Temp), colour="black") + labs(caption = "Black dots show interpolated points")

replacement_vancouver_2022 %>% ggplot() + geom_line(aes(x=Hour, y=Temp, group=JDay)) + labs(caption="These data look a tad suspicious")

replace_vancouver_all = bind_rows(vancouver2022int %>% select(Year, Month, Day, Hour, Temp))
for (i in seq_along(season_years_vancouver)){
  replace_vancouver_all = bind_rows(replace_vancouver_all,
  vancouver2022int %>% 
    select(Year, Month, Day, Hour, Temp) %>% 
    mutate(Year = case_when(Year==2021 ~ season_years_vancouver[i] -1L ,
                            Year==2022 ~ season_years_vancouver[i]))
  )
}
head(vancouver_DF %>% filter(Year==1977, Month==11))
head(replacement_vancouver_DF)
replacement_vancouver_DF_final = replacement_vancouver_DF %>% 
  rows_upsert(replace_vancouver_all, by = c("Year", "Month", "Day", "Hour")) %>% 
  group_by(Year, Month, Day) %>% 
  mutate(Date = ISOdate(Year, Month, Day, Hour),
         JDay = yday(Date)) %>% # without this there are NAs in the JDay and the traces separate a bit early
  ungroup() %>% 
  arrange(Date)
